{"term":"1973","caseName":"Howard Johnson Company, Inc. v. Detroit Local Joint Executive Board, Hotel & Restaurant Employees & Bartenders International Union, AFL-CIO","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1973/73-631","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 19, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16479","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll hear arguments next in 73-631, Howard Johnson Company against Detroit local.","start":0,"stop":30.416,"duration":30.42},{"text":"Mr. Tracy.","start":30.416,"stop":32.147,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":32.147,"stop":35.7,"duration":3.55},{"text":"This case is here as you know on writ of certiorari to the Court of Appeals from the Sixth Circuit.","start":35.7,"stop":42.118,"duration":6.42},{"text":"That Court affirmed a decision of the United States District Court which had held the petitioner, together with another employer, was required to arbitrate under the collective bargaining contract of the other employer.","start":42.118,"stop":61.652,"duration":19.53},{"text":"Actually, there were two other employers they are referred to in the brief as Grissoms and because there were several names, I will use that name for convenience.","start":61.652,"stop":75.323,"duration":13.67},{"text":"The issues presented are of whether petitioner is a successor employer as that term is used as a term of art in Labor Law, and whether petitioner is required to arbitrate grievances presented by Respondent Union under the contract between Respondent Union and the other employer, the Grissoms.","start":75.323,"stop":108.294,"duration":32.97},{"text":"The case arose with the beginning of June 1972 when petitioner, Howard Johnson Company entered into an agreement with his other employer as referred to as Grissoms, under which it was to buy a motel and a restaurant then being operated by the Grissoms who were franchisees of the Howard Johnson Company.","start":108.294,"stop":142.757,"duration":34.46},{"text":"That agreement provided for sale of certain assets in the motel and restaurant and for leasing of property on which they stood.","start":142.757,"stop":156.044,"duration":13.29},{"text":"It did not provide for assumption of contracts other than a contract with respect to advertising.","start":156.044,"stop":165.769,"duration":9.72},{"text":"On July 9, the -- excuse me -- on June 28, the Howard Johnson Company petitioner notified the seller that it would not assume the labor contract which the seller had with Respondent Union, two contracts existed.","start":165.769,"stop":187.468,"duration":21.7},{"text":"On July 9, the other employer notified its employees that they would be terminated at July 23.","start":187.468,"stop":201.015,"duration":13.55},{"text":"On July 13, the petitioner notified Respondent Union who had inquired at that time as to petitioner’s intent that it would not recognize the Union contract, which respondent had with the other employer.","start":201.015,"stop":220.613,"duration":19.6},{"text":"A few days later, the petitioner commenced interviewing prospective employees.","start":220.613,"stop":227.731,"duration":7.12},{"text":"It put advertisements in the local newspapers.","start":227.731,"stop":231.353,"duration":3.62},{"text":"Indeed, it put a sign in the very motel and restaurant where its business is being conducted, saying that it would be hiring employees.","start":231.353,"stop":242.754,"duration":11.4}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Did it conduct its business without interruption or did it stop for some period for changes, physical changes?","start":242.754,"stop":248.802,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"There was no stop, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":248.802,"stop":251.16,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Just a minute, between 11:59 and midnight?","start":251.16,"stop":252.676,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":252.676,"stop":253.654,"duration":0.98},{"text":"A contract ultimately called for closing at 12:01 am and the testimony is -- and this was put in on stipulated facts but the record is clear that at 12 o’clock, the franchisee discontinued its operations.]","start":253.654,"stop":269.623,"duration":15.97}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it you have conceived that that is a factor of some importance in the case.","start":269.623,"stop":275.213,"duration":5.59}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":275.213,"stop":278.354,"duration":3.14},{"text":"That certainly goes to the question of the meaning of a successor employer and I will certainly discuss that issue with the Court.","start":278.354,"stop":288.532,"duration":10.18},{"text":"The petitioner did hire employees.","start":288.532,"stop":292.957,"duration":4.43},{"text":"It hired some who had worked for this predecessor employer.","start":292.957,"stop":297.53,"duration":4.57},{"text":"Actually, it was 9 of the 33 I think in the restaurant and none of approximately 12 in the motel.","start":297.53,"stop":305.368,"duration":7.84},{"text":"It had a complete change of supervisory employees; none of the supervisory employees of the predecessor were retained.","start":305.368,"stop":314.042,"duration":8.67},{"text":"An entire new supervisory staff was brought in.","start":314.042,"stop":318.576,"duration":4.53},{"text":"The employees who were hired prior to July 24, the date on which the transaction was closed, were trained at another Howard Johnson facility which was nearby.","start":318.576,"stop":329.991,"duration":11.41},{"text":"And thereafter, on July 24, the transaction was ready for closing and that was a Sunday night or a Monday morning, but on the Friday preceding that, Respondent Union brought suit in state court seeking an injunction against what it termed “locking out” of employees and also seeking an order that both the predecessor employer and the petitioner should be required to submit to arbitration issues, which the Union desired to raise as to the rights of the employees to continue at their jobs as to the right of the Union to insist the collective bargaining continuing effect.","start":329.991,"stop":379.287,"duration":49.3},{"text":"And at a subsequent date, that case was removed to federal court.","start":379.287,"stop":387.104,"duration":7.82},{"text":"It was quickly submitted to the Court under Rule 65 or the Rules for Civil Procedure.","start":387.104,"stop":392.239,"duration":5.13},{"text":"There was an immediate final hearing.","start":392.239,"stop":394.971,"duration":2.73},{"text":"The case was submitted on stipulated facts.","start":394.971,"stop":398.546,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The Court was puzzled frankly as to appropriate application of this Court’s decision in National Labor Relations Board versus Burns and this Court’s decision in John Wiley and Sons versus Livingston, and the Court attempted to accommodate those two decisions.","start":398.546,"stop":422.393,"duration":23.85},{"text":"And we submit that the Court committed error.","start":422.393,"stop":426.998,"duration":4.61},{"text":"The Court of Appeals also faced the problem of the accommodation of Wiley and Burns.","start":426.998,"stop":439.921,"duration":12.92},{"text":"The District Court said that it was holding only that the Union’s request that the merit go to arbitration should be sustained, and that that did not necessarily mean that the contract in total should be applied.","start":439.921,"stop":464.335,"duration":24.41},{"text":"That was in recognition of the decision of this Court that a contract does not survive the transfer of a business, as stated in Burns.","start":464.335,"stop":477.535,"duration":13.2},{"text":"When that question got to the Court of Appeals, the same problem existed in the mind of the Court.","start":477.535,"stop":485.041,"duration":7.51},{"text":"This Court having said that the contract does not survive but nevertheless, this Court not having overruled Wiley what should be the application of this contract to this petition.","start":485.041,"stop":503.739,"duration":18.7},{"text":"I might point out unlike Wiley.","start":503.739,"stop":507.012,"duration":3.27},{"text":"In this case, there is still a predecessor employer.","start":507.012,"stop":511.968,"duration":4.96},{"text":"The entities, which I have referred to as Grissoms, appeared in the original proceeding, first in the State Court and in the United States District Court.","start":511.968,"stop":524.015,"duration":12.05},{"text":"They did not contest the Union’s request for arbitration.","start":524.015,"stop":529.226,"duration":5.21},{"text":"They stipulated that they will arbitrate the issues which the Union has sought to raise.","start":529.226,"stop":535.275,"duration":6.05},{"text":"So there will be an arbitration proceeding if the respondent desires to press that, and that as I say is a very large difference from the Wiley situation in which the predecessor employer had disappeared by merger.","start":535.275,"stop":552.179,"duration":16.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You don’t mean that Grissoms -- that the issue of whether some of the employees should be in the Howard Johnson, working for Howard Johnson is going to be arbitrated in any Grissoms arbitration?","start":552.179,"stop":563.763,"duration":11.58}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"No, if I could just -- no, Mr. Justice Brennan, I did not mean that in that proceeding that could --","start":563.763,"stop":568.754,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What issues other than in the Grissoms arbitration?","start":568.754,"stop":570.966,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue as to whether Grissoms have breached the contract they made with the respondent.","start":570.966,"stop":576.616,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Did they, when they agreed that that contract would be binding on themselves and successors, commit? That if they sold their business, they would require the successor to assume the contract.","start":576.616,"stop":588.192,"duration":11.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose the arbitrator concludes, yes, they did breach it. What’s the award?","start":588.192,"stop":593.595,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"An arbitrator has wide authority to make an appropriate award and in that case, I submit he could award money damages without question.","start":593.595,"stop":603.673,"duration":10.08},{"text":"I think that is his authority.","start":603.673,"stop":608.315,"duration":4.64},{"text":"So in this case, we come to the issue should this employer, the bound arbitrate, under that contract of the Grissoms.","start":608.315,"stop":620.213,"duration":11.9},{"text":"Now, the starting point of that is, is the employer a successor?","start":620.213,"stop":625.103,"duration":4.89},{"text":"And the difference between those case and in almost every case involving the definition of successor which has ever come up is that this employer did not employ more than a few of the employees of the predecessor, and the question becomes is the employment of at least a sufficient number of employees to constitute a majority --","start":625.103,"stop":647.737,"duration":22.63}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose the issue would have been here then even if Howard Johnson had employed none instead of nine?","start":647.737,"stop":654.469,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"In one of the two situations, Mr. Justice Brennan, there is none.","start":654.469,"stop":659.665,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s in the motels, right?","start":659.665,"stop":661.055,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":661.055,"stop":663.088,"duration":2.03},{"text":"There is a footnote in the Union brief which I think it’s page 22, which seems to indicate that maybe the petitioner has stated the Court Order in this case too broadly and that maybe all the District Court ordered was that there would be arbitration as to the effect on the employees the Union represents -- that’s what it says -- of the action that took place here.","start":663.088,"stop":693.956,"duration":30.87},{"text":"We think it is clear that the Union has sought broad arbitration and that indeed, it seeks to apply the entire contract although both the District Court and Court of Appeals have said, “The difference between those case in Burns is that unlike the Labor Board --.”","start":693.956,"stop":711.922,"duration":17.97},{"text":"And this is the Court of Appeals’ language, “the arbitrator could be selective in his application of the contract.","start":711.922,"stop":720.411,"duration":8.49},{"text":"He need not adopt an all or nothing approach.”","start":720.411,"stop":725.465,"duration":5.05},{"text":"Now we submit that that is not possible.","start":725.465,"stop":729.865,"duration":4.4},{"text":"The arbitrator as this Court has frequently recognized is a product of a contract.","start":729.865,"stop":738.143,"duration":8.28},{"text":"Arbitration is a voluntary contractual thing.","start":738.143,"stop":743.736,"duration":5.59},{"text":"Mr. Justice Powell in the recent case of Alexander versus Gardner-Denver noted limitation on the arbitrator.","start":743.736,"stop":752.889,"duration":9.15},{"text":"And in Gateway Coal, he noted that arbitration exists only when there is a contract to arbitrate.","start":752.889,"stop":761.607,"duration":8.72},{"text":"Now, the contract which is applicable in this case has a clause in it that says, “The arbitrator cannot add to, nor subtract from, nor modify the contract and no issue as to renewal or extension of the contract is subject to arbitration.”","start":761.607,"stop":782.828,"duration":21.22},{"text":"We submit that the Courts below have ignored that contract provision in suggesting that an arbitrator could somehow not take an all or nothing approach to the contract, that he could some way or another decide that some provisions of the contract should apply but not others.","start":782.828,"stop":803.263,"duration":20.44},{"text":"And we submit also that such an approach would leave an arbitrator completely contrary to the Burns’ decision of this Court.","start":803.263,"stop":813.051,"duration":9.79},{"text":"Now again, the arbitrator doesn’t have authority to make a new contract for the parties.","start":813.051,"stop":821.182,"duration":8.13},{"text":"His authority is to interpret a contract which the parties have made, but he cannot pick and choose among the provisions of the contract and say this will apply to this new employer, but this will not.","start":821.182,"stop":837.189,"duration":16.01},{"text":"And again, Mr. Justice Powell noted in the Gardner-Denver case that the arbitrator cannot go outside the contract.","start":837.189,"stop":848.07,"duration":10.88},{"text":"He went on in that case.","start":848.07,"stop":852.222,"duration":4.15},{"text":"The arbitrator really cannot even go to application of the Civil Rights Laws.","start":852.222,"stop":858.157,"duration":5.94},{"text":"He is limited to the application of the contract.","start":858.157,"stop":862.912,"duration":4.75},{"text":"Actually, what occurred here of course is the arbitrator is bound to accept the entire contract and clearly, he accepts the seniority provisions in the contract and his first ruling is that the petitioner should have taken all of these employees of the predecessor as its employees because they had seniority rights with the predecessor under this contract.","start":862.912,"stop":888.896,"duration":25.98},{"text":"Now if that is so of course, there is also a Union Recognition clause and a Union Bargaining Status Clause in the contract and presumably, the Union has now become the sole bargaining representative of the employees of petitioner.","start":888.896,"stop":907.543,"duration":18.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I take it -- especially this is in effect to say, although Burns said you didn’t have to hire anybody.","start":907.543,"stop":914.944,"duration":7.4},{"text":"If the Court of Appeals is right, this might be to fail to hire everybody?","start":914.944,"stop":919.335,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no question about it, Your Honor.","start":919.335,"stop":921.506,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So that’s really --","start":921.506,"stop":923.203,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":923.203,"stop":923.753,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the door of arbitration.","start":923.753,"stop":925.051,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"And that does away with the issue that -- the second issue that this Court considered in Burns, the question whether the Union is the majority representative if in fact we are bound to take all of these employees, of course the Union is then the representative and we then do have the Union with recognitional status.","start":925.051,"stop":948.144,"duration":23.09},{"text":"So the things that we decided in Burns just would not occur in this case.","start":948.144,"stop":955.035,"duration":6.89},{"text":"Now, should that be because this case came up in the context of a suit by the Union under Section 301 whereas Burns came up as an appeal from a National Labor Relations Board decision, and the Court of Appeals faced that squarely.","start":955.035,"stop":973.023,"duration":17.99},{"text":"They said there can be a dichotomy or can be two different rules.","start":973.023,"stop":977.575,"duration":4.55},{"text":"It is a contract in 301 but it’s not a contract in the Board.","start":977.575,"stop":983.291,"duration":5.72},{"text":"We submit this Court cannot let that ruling stand.","start":983.291,"stop":988.337,"duration":5.05}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Of course in Burns, the only connection between the Wackenhut and Burns was that the employees have been taken over.","start":988.337,"stop":995.147,"duration":6.81},{"text":"There was no acquisition of assets or of assumption of any liabilities.","start":995.147,"stop":1000.338,"duration":5.19},{"text":"And in here, you have got more of the latter, don’t you?","start":1000.338,"stop":1003.302,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"No question, Mr. Justice Rehnquist.","start":1003.302,"stop":1006.405,"duration":3.1},{"text":"We have here many of the criteria of successorship.","start":1006.405,"stop":1013.836,"duration":7.43},{"text":"The question is however, do we have the freedom to select our own labor force?","start":1013.836,"stop":1023.247,"duration":9.41},{"text":"If we do and if that is a crucial factor in determining whether an employer is a successor and we have not become a successor, and most of the statements of the criteria of successorship include the composition of the work force and the composition of the supervisory force.","start":1023.247,"stop":1049.044,"duration":25.8},{"text":"Now, we do not have those.","start":1049.044,"stop":1050.912,"duration":1.87},{"text":"I would like to conclude this portion of my argument and reserve the remainder of my time for rebuttal, but I submit that this Court should go back to the decision in Lincoln Mills as a starting point in the approach to this case.","start":1050.912,"stop":1067.634,"duration":16.72},{"text":"Lincoln Mills said that under Section 301, the Federal Courts are to apply a body of Federal Law developed from the intent of the Federal Labor Laws.","start":1067.634,"stop":1081.019,"duration":13.38},{"text":"The intent of the Federal Labor Law is clear; there must be majority status in order for the Union to gain recognition.","start":1081.019,"stop":1091.676,"duration":10.66},{"text":"There cannot be a contract in a court proceeding but no contract in a Board proceeding.","start":1091.676,"stop":1099.751,"duration":8.08},{"text":"That is completely contrary to the spirit of Lincoln Mills.","start":1099.751,"stop":1104.456,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Thank you Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1104.456,"stop":1109.377,"duration":4.92}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gold.","start":1109.377,"stop":1113.352,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court.","start":1113.352,"stop":1117.553,"duration":4.2},{"text":"Analytically, there are two issues in this type of case which for convenience we refer through -- refer to throughout our brief as a Wiley type case, since that is the leading authority in the field.","start":1117.553,"stop":1135.612,"duration":18.06},{"text":"The first is whether the second employer is a successor as that term has been used in the Section 301 law in the second case.","start":1135.612,"stop":1148.41,"duration":12.8},{"text":"The second question --","start":1148.41,"stop":1149.377,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the common statute?","start":1149.377,"stop":1150.816,"duration":1.44},{"text":"That is a Board construct I guess, is it not?","start":1150.816,"stop":1154.595,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"The successorship concept, Mr. Justice White?","start":1154.595,"stop":1161.065,"duration":6.47},{"text":"There was Board law on the concept of successorship before this Court decided Wiley.","start":1161.065,"stop":1169.251,"duration":8.19}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"We understand that, but I mean it was -- it’s a Board, it’s an NLRB construction that came about in applying the Act.","start":1169.251,"stop":1180.818,"duration":11.57}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I am -- what I was trying to do in answering your question was say there are antecedents in the Board law of the successorship concept.","start":1180.818,"stop":1189.658,"duration":8.84},{"text":"But it is our view that the Section 301 law of successorship is not the same as the Board Law, and that the law as declared in Wiley is not the same as of the law which had developed in the Board, either in terms of the test of successorship or in terms of the consequence of a finding those successorship.","start":1189.658,"stop":1211.693,"duration":22.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But there’s nothing -- there’s nothing in the labor law expressly dealing with successorship, is there?","start":1211.693,"stop":1217.23,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Nothing.","start":1217.23,"stop":1217.779,"duration":0.55},{"text":"There are no words in 301 to which we look for guidance.","start":1217.779,"stop":1221.14,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So your -- the successorship concept is used as a vehicle to apply a certain section in the labor law?","start":1221.14,"stop":1230.145,"duration":9}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes --","start":1230.145,"stop":1231.015,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Such as the duty to bargain?","start":1231.015,"stop":1232.749,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1232.749,"stop":1233.303,"duration":0.55},{"text":"One is the duty to bargain and the --","start":1233.303,"stop":1234.653,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And whether you are bound by a contract?","start":1234.653,"stop":1236.589,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1236.589,"stop":1238.906,"duration":2.32},{"text":"And it is our view that --","start":1238.906,"stop":1241.856,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And the -- the provision that says you are not bound by a contract, unless you agree to it, is subject to the Board has held before Burns anyway that it was subject to an exception that the successor is bound if he is a successor, as defined by the Board.","start":1241.856,"stop":1260.911,"duration":19.06}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Board law preceded in by stating different rules at different times.","start":1260.911,"stop":1270.74,"duration":9.83},{"text":"The Board law at the time Wiley was decided was that a successor as the Board use that term was not bound by the agreement.","start":1270.74,"stop":1281.158,"duration":10.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1281.158,"stop":1281.537,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"They reverse themselves in Burns.","start":1281.537,"stop":1283.006,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In Burns, yes.","start":1283.006,"stop":1284.045,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1284.045,"stop":1285.039,"duration":0.99},{"text":"But this Court held that in a 301 case, the successor is bound by his predecessor’s duty to arbitrate.","start":1285.039,"stop":1294.189,"duration":9.15},{"text":"That was the holding in Wiley.","start":1294.189,"stop":1297.054,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":1297.054,"stop":1298.191,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"And in Burns, you again dealt with the Board law, which was the duty to bargain law.","start":1298.191,"stop":1305.71,"duration":7.52},{"text":"Now, I am really not sure that I have been at all responsive to the question.","start":1305.71,"stop":1312.396,"duration":6.69}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, nothing in Wiley suggested what does the arbitrator would have open for decision and what would be the signpost for him to proceed about under.","start":1312.396,"stop":1327.01,"duration":14.61}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it did not map it out for him.","start":1327.01,"stop":1330.997,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The arbitrator might have open only, whether or not the -- only whether or not the buyer or the surviving corporation promised -- made some promises along the way that might bind them.","start":1330.997,"stop":1342.722,"duration":11.72}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1342.722,"stop":1343.077,"duration":0.36},{"text":"There were specific arbitration issues which had been posed in Wiley.","start":1343.077,"stop":1348.431,"duration":5.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that, but what would be open for the arbitrator to decide?","start":1348.431,"stop":1354.519,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean in deciding any of those specific issues?","start":1354.519,"stop":1356.811,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1356.811,"stop":1358.202,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"My understanding of the direction in Wiley is that what’s open for the arbitrator to decide is whether those portions of the agreement continue to be a -- to create a subsidy of rules of the continuing business enterprise.","start":1358.202,"stop":1378.368,"duration":20.17},{"text":"And it’s our view, as stated in the briefs that in doing that job, he is to look to change circumstances in the equity of the situation, that what we have here is not something which is sui generis but rather a type of arbitration which was contemplated in the Steelworker’s trilogy.","start":1378.368,"stop":1399.24,"duration":20.87},{"text":"In the Steelworker’s trilogy, the Court emphasized the fact that the arbitrator is to take into account changed circumstances, even in a situation in which there are not sufficient changed circumstances so that the second employer is not a successor and not bound by the arbitration clause.","start":1399.24,"stop":1416.562,"duration":17.32},{"text":"There may be factors which it has to meet an incumbent upon the arbitrative taken to account in determining the successor’s obligations.","start":1416.562,"stop":1425.849,"duration":9.29},{"text":"And that’s what we think Wiley directed the arbitrators to do, and that is what they have been doing.","start":1425.849,"stop":1431.583,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But you don’t know what Wiley would have said if the successor corporation -- if that had been a purchase of assets case and if the buyer had hired none of the employees of the predecessor, you have no idea what Wiley would have said?","start":1431.583,"stop":1447.872,"duration":16.29}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"We know certain things about what Wiley would have said.","start":1447.872,"stop":1451.119,"duration":3.25},{"text":"First of all --","start":1451.119,"stop":1451.401,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You don’t know whether it went aboard to arbitration?","start":1451.401,"stop":1454.448,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"First of all, we know that in the view of the Wiley court, the merger situation was considered a less likely one than the assets acquisition situation for application of the successorship doctrine, because that is what the Court said.","start":1454.448,"stop":1470.875,"duration":16.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well -- but you don’t know what it would have said in view of the -- if there had not been any employees taken over?","start":1470.875,"stop":1477.179,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we do not know precisely what they would have said, but we do know what the general proposition that is --","start":1477.179,"stop":1483.031,"duration":5.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is one of the elements in deciding successorship in the first place, isn’t it?","start":1483.031,"stop":1486.157,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"We do not believe so.","start":1486.157,"stop":1488.297,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Or it used to be.","start":1488.297,"stop":1489.745,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"It has never been so far as we know an element in the Section 301 Law of successorship.","start":1489.745,"stop":1496.396,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that’s just your -- that’s the root.","start":1496.396,"stop":1500.132,"duration":3.74},{"text":"That originated with Wiley, I take it.","start":1500.132,"stop":1502.272,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1502.272,"stop":1503.379,"duration":1.11},{"text":"But Section 30 --","start":1503.379,"stop":1503.586,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You don’t know what Wiley would have said if there had not -- if there had been a situation where there were not any former employees involved?","start":1503.586,"stop":1512.595,"duration":9.01}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we don’t know in the sense that in that case, we -- in that case, the employer, although not originally over mind to it, eventually did hire the employees.","start":1512.595,"stop":1524.248,"duration":11.65},{"text":"But we do know that there are certain basic principles.","start":1524.248,"stop":1526.65,"duration":2.4},{"text":"First of all, we know that in Wiley, the successorship test was stated to be whether there are any substantial indicia of continuity and that it used the fact that the second employer hired the employees as saying that that was evidence of continuity, not that it was a necessary condition.","start":1526.65,"stop":1547.075,"duration":20.42},{"text":"And we do know that the general rule stated in Wiley is that it would be inconsistent with our holding that the obligation to arbitrate survived the merger, where we to hold that the fact of the merger without more removed claims otherwise plainly arbitrable from the scope of the arbitration clause?","start":1547.075,"stop":1567.989,"duration":20.91},{"text":"That’s at page 554 376 U.S.","start":1567.989,"stop":1571.7,"duration":3.71},{"text":"Well, the issue -- the claims --","start":1571.7,"stop":1573.553,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll resume there at 10 o’clock in the morning.","start":1573.553,"stop":1577.423,"duration":3.87}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 20, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16816","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gold, I think you have about 22 minutes remaining.","start":0,"stop":10.969,"duration":10.97}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":10.969,"stop":13.934,"duration":2.97},{"text":"To briefly put the matter back in focus, this is a Section 301 suit to compel arbitration.","start":13.934,"stop":27.209,"duration":13.28},{"text":"The problem it raises is whether the duty to arbitrate survives over a change in the identity of owners, where that change takes place against the background of a collective agreement enforced and is brought about by negotiations between the first employer and the purchaser.","start":27.209,"stop":53.871,"duration":26.66},{"text":"At the afternoon recess yesterday, I was endeavoring to respond to Mr. Justice White’s questions concerning the scope of Wiley versus Livingston which was also a Section 301 case presenting the same issue.","start":53.871,"stop":74.096,"duration":20.23},{"text":"Naturally, Wiley like every other president leaves certain leeways in the law, but it is a recent decision and I hope we’ll be able to demonstrate that if rooted in basic precepts of the National Labor Policy, and is not simply a decision which can be read to settle the particular facts there before the Court.","start":74.096,"stop":102.143,"duration":28.05},{"text":"To understand its lessons, we believe it’s necessary to analyze its basic rationale.","start":102.143,"stop":111.516,"duration":9.37},{"text":"Firstly, --","start":111.516,"stop":111.995,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"I think someone asked you yesterday, and I don’t have your answer precisely in mind, Mr. Gold.","start":111.995,"stop":119.462,"duration":7.47},{"text":"What is the scope of the arbitration agreement assuming arbitration is compelled?","start":119.462,"stop":128.4,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"There are two aspects to that Mr. Chief Justice.","start":128.4,"stop":130.995,"duration":2.59},{"text":"First, we look at the scope of the arbitration agreement if one means what are the subsequent obligations which the second employer is bound by to be essentially equivalent to the process of arbitration mapped out in the Steelworkers’ trilogy.","start":130.995,"stop":157.99,"duration":27},{"text":"Namely that in the arbitration, the arbitrator is bound by the agreement, but he is to take into account changed circumstances and the different equities of the parties, and to fulfill his role as the expositor of the contractual law set out in the agreement.","start":157.99,"stop":187.552,"duration":29.56},{"text":"Naturally, the assumption is that there will be more need for a creative and sensitive application of the agreement where there is a new employer, because he brings different insights, different presuppositions, and he may make certain changes within his permitted scope under the Managerial Prerogatives Clause which this agreement has, which may substantially change this situation.","start":187.552,"stop":219.138,"duration":31.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Gold, is that to subsume that the agreement itself then survives the sale?","start":219.138,"stop":224.649,"duration":5.51}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"It survives to the extent that the arbitrator finds it to be -- to comport with the changed situation.","start":224.649,"stop":237.073,"duration":12.42},{"text":"It is the framework, the duty to arbitrate survives and the arbitrator is to determine the subsequent obligations that survive.","start":237.073,"stop":248.239,"duration":11.17}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that in other words, the obligations upon the successor to the business?","start":248.239,"stop":253.858,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":253.858,"stop":254.774,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the arbitrator isn’t bound by the contract, what framework does he use to determine what obligations survive?","start":254.774,"stop":261.726,"duration":6.95}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"The answer that I was attempting to give is that my understanding is that he is bound by the framework of the contract.","start":261.726,"stop":267.953,"duration":6.23},{"text":"He cannot toss it over his shoulder and act as a someone who is making law, but he can take into account reasoned arguments from the second employer that changed circumstances, or different equities makes specific provisions inapplicable.","start":267.953,"stop":288.512,"duration":20.56},{"text":"It seems to us that that is the role that Wiley envisages and that’s what in essence the arbitrators have been doing in the --","start":288.512,"stop":299.142,"duration":10.63}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean Wiley then to say not only there’s a duty to arbitrate but the framework of the arbitration is the existing contract?","start":299.142,"stop":306.755,"duration":7.61}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, because if that were not true, then we would have to agree with the company that the task would not be a principled one, but we do think that the task is a principled one, and we do think that the flexibility is there in the sense that the arbitrator, just as he can under the Steelworkers trilogy, but to take into account changed situations and changed equities.","start":306.755,"stop":333.371,"duration":26.62}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what are the clauses in the contract is a recognition of the Union, is it not?","start":333.371,"stop":337.91,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"But that is the type of clause depending on the situation which may not survive.","start":337.91,"stop":343.028,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Obviously, if the clause is contrary to law, let’s take the Wiley situation.","start":343.028,"stop":347.687,"duration":4.66},{"text":"In Wiley, the unit of Interscience employees, that was the entity that was merged into Wiley was 40 people, and if we take -- those 40 people were transferred into a unit which already had 300, then there would be no duty to recognize, and obviously to the extent that you have any other such clauses that don’t survive the change because of that type changed circumstances --","start":347.687,"stop":380.301,"duration":32.61}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Gold, what about the steps that precede arbitration that the contract probably requires?","start":380.301,"stop":390.07,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean grievance?","start":390.07,"stop":391.016,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":391.016,"stop":391.635,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Filing grievances and so on?","start":391.635,"stop":392.651,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":392.651,"stop":393.697,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"We would assume that the process would continue --","start":393.697,"stop":401.2,"duration":7.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That is at the successor then has to negotiate, whatever the grievance may be, or attempt to negotiate that settlement with the Union representatives on exhaust type before the Government?","start":401.2,"stop":413.008,"duration":11.81}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the Union representatives for the people --","start":413.008,"stop":416.062,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn’t that recognition?","start":416.062,"stop":417.649,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because it seems to us that the very point of your decision in Lion Dry Goods was that there can be situations in which the employer treats on a “members only” representative basis, and in a situation in which the Union doesn’t have a majority, that would be the result of a Wiley holding.","start":417.649,"stop":444.731,"duration":27.08}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, realistically what we’re talking about here, I gather, is the grievance of the separation of these, what is it, 41 employees.","start":444.731,"stop":453.051,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":453.051,"stop":453.957,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And that we say that the employer is free when he purchases this business, not to continue the employment of anybody in the unit, he did in this instance, employee 9, but the 41 say “Well you couldn’t have separated us.”","start":453.957,"stop":471.469,"duration":17.51},{"text":"And that becomes a grievance and this all has to go through the grievance procedure before they get services?","start":471.469,"stop":476.12,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, --","start":476.12,"stop":477.148,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But, this in part of your submission is that if the arbitrator could decide to put all 41 back to work?.","start":477.148,"stop":483.038,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes sir.","start":483.038,"stop":484.116,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And which means that the successor does not have the right not to hire that he must perhaps take over the old employees?","start":484.116,"stop":493.33,"duration":9.21}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":493.33,"stop":494.945,"duration":1.62},{"text":"In Golden State --","start":494.945,"stop":497.388,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And you say that’s because of successorship?","start":497.388,"stop":500.103,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":500.103,"stop":501.508,"duration":1.4},{"text":"In Golden State, Mr. Justice Brennan pointed out, that I’m reading the reproduction of this passage from the Golden State opinion which is the most recent successorship case.","start":501.508,"stop":520.322,"duration":18.81},{"text":"Although, again one of arising of a different context since our view that each of these areas are discreet, but they throw a cross light on each other.","start":520.322,"stop":529.855,"duration":9.53},{"text":"This is on page 28 of our brief, blue brief.","start":529.855,"stop":534.943,"duration":5.09},{"text":"For example, because the purchaser is not obligated by the act to hire any of the predecessor’s employees C. Burns, the purchaser if it does not hire or any, or a majority of those employees will not be bound by an outstanding audit to bargain issued by the Board against the predecessor, nor by any order tied to the continuance of the bargaining agent in the unit involved, and that is a position which we understand and accept.","start":534.943,"stop":567.363,"duration":32.42},{"text":"The Act does not require an employer to hire anyone, and that is what this says.","start":567.363,"stop":576.253,"duration":8.89},{"text":"An employer, as long as he doesn’t act for any to Union reasons has the right to --","start":576.253,"stop":582.908,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but as a practical matter Mr. Gold, your submission is, but if there’s an arbitration clause under 301 well, he has no obligation to hire.","start":582.908,"stop":593.169,"duration":10.26},{"text":"The arbitrator may order him to re-employ all 41.","start":593.169,"stop":597.259,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, what I’m trying to say is that there is no statutory obligation prior, but there maybe a contractual obligation to hire.","start":597.259,"stop":605.051,"duration":7.79},{"text":"Contracts are -- the contractual obligations are not equal to statutory obligations.","start":605.051,"stop":610.828,"duration":5.78},{"text":"There are different concepts of successorship here --","start":610.828,"stop":613.451,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"One of the difficulties for me is that if it’s true that to this extent, the contract is binding on the successor.","start":613.451,"stop":621.436,"duration":7.99},{"text":"Then I have a difficulty seeing why this in finding out a successor in all respects including recognition.","start":621.436,"stop":627.801,"duration":6.37}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it may or may not be.","start":627.801,"stop":629.228,"duration":1.43},{"text":"There are situations in which --","start":629.228,"stop":630.326,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if they put all 41 back to work, there certainly is going to be a duty to bargain, because there’s going to be all the employees in the unit.","start":630.326,"stop":638.218,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there’s no duty to bargain in the sense that there is -- under the scheme, the duty to bargain with sense to negotiate under the scheme, there is a negotiation during the term.","start":638.218,"stop":650.523,"duration":12.31},{"text":"There maybe a duty to recognize depending on -- the situation depending on the composition of the work force, but to say that because in this case, if the employer has to hire the predecessor’s employees, there’s a duty to recognize, there will always be, is incorrect.","start":650.523,"stop":674.575,"duration":24.05},{"text":"And I think the Wiley situation indicates it.","start":674.575,"stop":676.729,"duration":2.15},{"text":"There maybe mergers which also merge a small unit in place into a larger one, in that case, there wouldn’t be the duty to recognize.","start":676.729,"stop":684.551,"duration":7.82},{"text":"But way of it is a duty to hire, then the duty to recognize may follow with it as being a part of the agreement that still fits.","start":684.551,"stop":694.562,"duration":10.01},{"text":"And --","start":694.562,"stop":694.67,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"How about those newly employed by Howard Johnson, would they have any claim under the old contract?","start":694.67,"stop":702.905,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"I would not think so.","start":702.905,"stop":705.867,"duration":2.96},{"text":"The very theory they may have, to the extent that they survived the first arbitration and choose to be represented by the employees, but at the present time, Howard Johnson has hired them under the common law system under which he can discharge him at will.","start":705.867,"stop":727.599,"duration":21.73},{"text":"The only people who the Union is seeking to represent and those who have authorized to represent them, namely the predecessor’s employees and the policy of Wiley is to cushion the shock of the change on most predecessor’s employees, and to carry forward the contractual obligations.","start":727.599,"stop":751.601,"duration":24},{"text":"If the employer discharged them wrongly, then they deserve to be protected.","start":751.601,"stop":756.766,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"So, that if the arbitrator declined to require the rehiring of the 41, basically it’s only the nine that would have the right to --","start":756.766,"stop":767.177,"duration":10.41}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"The nine or any others who chose to ask the Union to represent them.","start":767.177,"stop":771.648,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Any new people.","start":771.648,"stop":772.846,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, any new people would choose to represent them, because then you would be in a situation where you have members on the agreement.","start":772.846,"stop":782.474,"duration":9.63},{"text":"But the point that I was trying to make in terms of the statutory obligation, the contractual obligation, I think is simply illustrated by the case where you have only one employer, and an employe is discharged because he gets on the wrong side of his foreman.","start":782.474,"stop":798.843,"duration":16.37},{"text":"If he goes to the National Labor Relations Board, he doesn’t get any relief because the Board has no plenary authority to readdress unjust discharges.","start":798.843,"stop":812.348,"duration":13.5},{"text":"On the other hand, if he’s under an agreement and he goes to an arbitrator, he can get relief.","start":812.348,"stop":817.236,"duration":4.89},{"text":"So, the fact that there isn’t a statutory obligation on an employer, which is what Burns holds.","start":817.236,"stop":823.222,"duration":5.99},{"text":"There is no statutory obligation which we can extrapolate.","start":823.222,"stop":826.553,"duration":3.33},{"text":"From 8 (a) 5 to recognize an agreement or to hire employees doesn’t mean that there is no contractual obligation.","start":826.553,"stop":834.754,"duration":8.2}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes but the access if some says that an employer isn’t obligated to honor a contract that he hasn’t agreed to, but the Act doesn’t impose a contract him and he must agree to it.","start":834.754,"stop":848.074,"duration":13.32},{"text":"Now, you’re saying that a Union and an employer act by signing an agreement that says that “this contract binds successors.”","start":848.074,"stop":859.159,"duration":11.09}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that’s right.","start":859.159,"stop":859.546,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Automatically will bind successors in spite of the fact that the successor rights learn say “I’m not going to bound, and does not tend to be bound,” and relies on the Act’s provision that “I’m not bound unless I agree.”","start":859.546,"stop":872.121,"duration":12.57}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that helps me get back to where I was starting from, because I think that that’s really the question of what Wiley says.","start":872.121,"stop":885.109,"duration":12.99},{"text":"And what Wiley says in the theory of it is that he point of collective agreements, and here I quote the House Report, or paraphrase the House Report on the Wagner Act “The plaintiff collected bargaining is not to start a process which is a means in itself, but it’s a means to an end.”","start":885.109,"stop":908.837,"duration":23.73},{"text":"And the end is collective agreements which stabilize the terms and conditions of employment for certain period of time.","start":908.837,"stop":916.673,"duration":7.84},{"text":"And the practice of collective bargaining, as this Court has recognized in Warrior and Gulf, is to attempt to elect a system of self -- industrial self government which controls a specific business enterprise.","start":916.673,"stop":932.912,"duration":16.24},{"text":"It sets the terms on which the employees deals with each other, and which they deal with the employer, and it binds employees who come into the unit after the fact.","start":932.912,"stop":943.433,"duration":10.52},{"text":"It binds those who would not have supported the Union in the first place, and indeed to push for stability is so great, that if the employees change their mind during the term, they can’t get a Board election in which to express that, that’s the contract by rules.","start":943.433,"stop":961.099,"duration":17.67},{"text":"And because of all that in one of the early leading cases this Court said, that the collective agreement is analogous to a tariff, or to a Government utility rates which bind all those who come within its terms.","start":961.099,"stop":976.719,"duration":15.62},{"text":"The theory upon which the parties operate is that so long as the business enterprise continues, these rules which has setup will continue, and what Mr. Justice Powell said for the Court --","start":976.719,"stop":991.501,"duration":14.78}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that maybe that the rules continue, but the basic question here is to what employees do they apply?","start":991.501,"stop":1002.17,"duration":10.67}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it’s beyond that.","start":1002.17,"stop":1002.767,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And that maybe --","start":1002.767,"stop":1003.264,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me it’s when does it change in the identity of the employer change those rules.","start":1003.264,"stop":1010.78,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they don’t want to be changing the rules, it just that even if you said that the same rules apply to the successor, you could still say that he may bring his own employees along.","start":1010.78,"stop":1022.098,"duration":11.32}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no, one of the rules is that the just cause and seniority provisions of the agreement apply.","start":1022.098,"stop":1033.04,"duration":10.94},{"text":"That is probably the most important aspect of the bargain from the union and the employees' standpoint.","start":1033.04,"stop":1039.067,"duration":6.03},{"text":"And if --","start":1039.067,"stop":1039.165,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You certainly are taking quite a bite out of Burns, I suppose, in these cases, in that argument.","start":1039.165,"stop":1043.345,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not believe so.","start":1043.345,"stop":1047.086,"duration":3.74},{"text":"It’s our theory that the cases stand together, after all in your opinion, you distinguished Wiley.","start":1047.086,"stop":1055.526,"duration":8.44},{"text":"Our view is that there is a difference between the statutory obligations which can be drawn from Section 8 (a) (5) and the contractual obligations which can be implied as a matter of law just as the basic duty of arbitrators imply, and just as a no strike agreement can be implied, as this Court did in Lucas Flower.","start":1055.526,"stop":1078.845,"duration":23.32},{"text":"The very theory of contractual enforcement is that these duties can be implied by the Court.","start":1078.845,"stop":1088.659,"duration":9.81},{"text":"And what Burns says is that the Board has a more limited authority, but that doesn’t seem to us to undercut the Board’s authority.","start":1088.659,"stop":1097.438,"duration":8.78},{"text":"Indeed, in the AFL-CIO brief, the (Inaudible) brief.","start":1097.438,"stop":1101.578,"duration":4.14},{"text":"We quoted from C&C Plywood decision by Mr. Justice Stewart, in which he draws the point that when Congress made its decision to give the Courts the authority to enforce agreements, it rejected giving that authority to the Board, this is on page 6, because that would be Government compulsion of the terms and conditions of employment.","start":1101.578,"stop":1133.881,"duration":32.3},{"text":"But that authority given to the Courts isn’t the same, because the Courts are not deriving the obligations they state from the statute.","start":1133.881,"stop":1145.554,"duration":11.67},{"text":"They are deriving them from the contract.","start":1145.554,"stop":1149.724,"duration":4.17},{"text":"The contract is interpreted in the normal way Courts interpret contracts.","start":1149.724,"stop":1154.812,"duration":5.09},{"text":"And I just want to conclude by saying that there are three basic choices open in Wiley, either the continuity with business enterprise the test drawn from the understanding of collective agreements would apply, or else the employer would be able to choose or not choose whether to be bound, and if he were able to choose or not choose whether to be bound, that would create an extraordinary disparity, because the employees would be at the second employer’s mercy.","start":1154.812,"stop":1183.631,"duration":28.82},{"text":"The value of their bargain would depend on whether or not he thought it was a good bargain.","start":1183.631,"stop":1188.552,"duration":4.92},{"text":"If he thinks it’s a good bargain, he can say “I accept it.”","start":1188.552,"stop":1192.173,"duration":3.62},{"text":"But if he thinks it’s a bad bargain, he can say “I reject it.”","start":1192.173,"stop":1195.035,"duration":2.86},{"text":"On the other hand, the employees have to take whichever way he jumps.","start":1195.035,"stop":1199.685,"duration":4.65},{"text":"And that seems to us to be completely inconsistent --","start":1199.685,"stop":1202.111,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, here on your approach, the successor employer, whether he thinks it’s bad or good is bound by the contract.","start":1202.111,"stop":1209.634,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, if he is a successor --","start":1209.634,"stop":1211.169,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"In a contract that he never negotiated.","start":1211.169,"stop":1214.331,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"But Wiley says that by buying the business, knowing of the agreement and continuing the business so that it is of continuity, he steps into the shoes of his predecessor.","start":1214.331,"stop":1226.299,"duration":11.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The contract runs with the business --","start":1226.299,"stop":1228.185,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":1228.185,"stop":1228.435,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it’s like something else runs with the land.","start":1228.435,"stop":1231.377,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1231.377,"stop":1234.589,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"There’s a lot of difference.","start":1234.589,"stop":1237.322,"duration":2.73},{"text":"Normally contracts don’t run with the business.","start":1237.322,"stop":1241.741,"duration":4.42}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, some contracts do.","start":1241.741,"stop":1244.086,"duration":2.35},{"text":"I mean, the common law rule is not the only rule as Mr. Justice Rehnquist pointed out in his opinion in Burns.","start":1244.086,"stop":1256.144,"duration":12.06},{"text":"There are obligations which are imposed on successors, or people who take over business as a matter of law.","start":1256.144,"stop":1264.859,"duration":8.71},{"text":"And I want to make --","start":1264.859,"stop":1266.444,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"My own problem is it doesn’t do it in and of itself.","start":1266.444,"stop":1269.795,"duration":3.35},{"text":"I thought you said the contract in and of itself work with the business despite what the land said. It’s not just in and of itself.","start":1269.795,"stop":1279.178,"duration":9.38}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it’s the contract right in terms of National Labor Policy in the presumptions and its meaning, and I just want to note that in this case, there is a Successorship Clause.","start":1279.178,"stop":1289.469,"duration":10.29},{"text":"If the predecessor -- if the only remedy is against the predecessor, we have a situation which we think is -- which is analogous to that in Boeing’s markets.","start":1289.469,"stop":1300.295,"duration":10.83},{"text":"All you can get is damages, but that isn’t the purpose of the Labor Law.","start":1300.295,"stop":1303.619,"duration":3.32},{"text":"The Labor Law is opposed to the Law of Commercial Contracts.","start":1303.619,"stop":1308.677,"duration":5.06},{"text":"Specific performance is what is sought when you have an arbitration or its common law and no strike provision, and the only way you can have that is the method employed by Wiley, which is to say that this situation is not the same as one in which there is no contract.","start":1308.677,"stop":1325.246,"duration":16.57},{"text":"There is a contract and the successor steps into it.","start":1325.246,"stop":1328.298,"duration":3.05},{"text":"And I want to point out how close the continuity is in this case.","start":1328.298,"stop":1332.127,"duration":3.83},{"text":"How Johnson had a voice in this business before the change.","start":1332.127,"stop":1337.397,"duration":5.27},{"text":"There was its franchisee.","start":1337.397,"stop":1340.778,"duration":3.38},{"text":"Before and after the change, there was a Howard Johnson’s Motel selling basically the same things to the same class of costumers.","start":1340.778,"stop":1348.996,"duration":8.22},{"text":"Before and after the change, there was a discreet unit of 55 people who were working for that employer.","start":1348.996,"stop":1356.733,"duration":7.74},{"text":"There was a one minute hiatus as both Mr. Justice Stewart and the Chief Justice pointed out yesterday.","start":1356.733,"stop":1363.28,"duration":6.55},{"text":"If this employer is in the successor, we don’t’ know who he is.","start":1363.28,"stop":1366.345,"duration":3.07},{"text":"And if he is a successor, then there was never a break in the contractual obligations, and those contractual obligations were his just as there were his predecessor’s.","start":1366.345,"stop":1381.435,"duration":15.09}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"But that’s sound defining almost.","start":1381.435,"stop":1384.277,"duration":2.84},{"text":"You say the man is a successor, and therefore, there never was a break in his contractual obligations.","start":1384.277,"stop":1390.817,"duration":6.54},{"text":"You’ve still got to make the case for the successorship.","start":1390.817,"stop":1396.583,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that’s right.","start":1396.583,"stop":1397.562,"duration":0.98},{"text":"I think our first duty is to show that there is a continuity of the business enterprise which makes it proper to say the second employer is a successor.","start":1397.562,"stop":1407.403,"duration":9.84},{"text":"Where there isn’t a continuity, then he is not a successor and he is not bound by the arbitration clause, or any of the other potential obligations which are in the agreement.","start":1407.403,"stop":1418.783,"duration":11.38},{"text":"And --","start":1418.783,"stop":1419.25,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But in deciding successorship, I take it you put aside the fact that he may not have hired any of the old employees.","start":1419.25,"stop":1425.977,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, because we think that the background of the law is different that if that is the test, then the very issue to be are he can control whether or not there’s to be an arbitration by disregarding a potential obligation, and therefore, that the situation is different from the situation under 8 (a) (5).","start":1425.977,"stop":1447.251,"duration":21.27},{"text":"Under Section 8 (a) (5), first of all, there’s no obligation, and secondly you look to the employee complement because you’re asking whether or not there should be negotiations for new agreement whether there’s a duty to recognize.","start":1447.251,"stop":1460.382,"duration":13.13},{"text":"And the duty to recognize stands from the employee free choice.","start":1460.382,"stop":1464.392,"duration":4.01},{"text":"Employee free choice is subordinated to stability during the term of the agreement, and that’s why you don’t look to the employer-employee complement in a contract case, but rather as Mr. Justice Rehnquist pointed out, and certainly what he said is applicable in this case, you look to continuity on the employer side, continuity in the business enterprise.","start":1464.392,"stop":1486.747,"duration":22.36},{"text":"And if that is there, then the duty to arbitrate does follow.","start":1486.747,"stop":1490.908,"duration":4.16},{"text":"That is the theory which we are arguing.","start":1490.908,"stop":1493.333,"duration":2.43},{"text":"We’re saying that we have to show the successorship.","start":1493.333,"stop":1496.395,"duration":3.06},{"text":"We have to show a lack of discontinuity.","start":1496.395,"stop":1498.918,"duration":2.52},{"text":"We think we have all sorts of continuity here, and once we have that, then the duty to arbitration does flows to conclusion.","start":1498.918,"stop":1506.441,"duration":7.52},{"text":"That is our position.","start":1506.441,"stop":1508.255,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you would agree then that by your test of successorship, there wasn’t successorship between Wackenhut and Burns.","start":1508.255,"stop":1516.987,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"In the contractual sense.","start":1516.987,"stop":1518.235,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"In the contractual sense.","start":1518.235,"stop":1518.742,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Laurence Stephen Gold","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t think that that’s a different case.","start":1518.742,"stop":1520.556,"duration":1.81},{"text":"Now, there have been developments since you wrote your opinion which may have some effect on that case, the Service Contract Act Amendments which are quoted in the AFL-CIO brief.","start":1520.556,"stop":1532.473,"duration":11.92},{"text":"But as a matter of basic first impression in the contract law, if there is not continuity on the employer’s side, we do agree that there isn’t a 301 obligation.","start":1532.473,"stop":1547.52,"duration":15.05}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"You have anything further Mr. Tracy?","start":1547.52,"stop":1551.56,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":1551.56,"stop":1553.694,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"May I just ask Mr. Tracy, I gather in your submission, had Howard Johnson taken on all of predecessor’s employees, Howard Johnson still would not be bound by the contract?","start":1553.694,"stop":1570.365,"duration":16.67}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we believe that is what this Court said in Burns.","start":1570.365,"stop":1573.367,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you might have had a duty to argue?","start":1573.367,"stop":1575.052,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"No doubt, Your Honor, no question whatever.","start":1575.052,"stop":1577.445,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But you would not be bound at all by the agreement?","start":1577.445,"stop":1580.24,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it so happens that I was the attorney for an employer in a case which was a companion to the Burns case at the Board, and my client desired that the contract continue in effect.","start":1580.24,"stop":1592.657,"duration":12.42},{"text":"The Union did not.","start":1592.657,"stop":1594.983,"duration":2.33},{"text":"The company had been bought by a larger company.","start":1594.983,"stop":1598.205,"duration":3.22},{"text":"The Union saw an opportunity to negotiate a better contract.","start":1598.205,"stop":1603.143,"duration":4.94},{"text":"The Board, as you know in Burns, said the contract did continue.","start":1603.143,"stop":1609.085,"duration":5.94},{"text":"The case in which I was involved was never appealed.","start":1609.085,"stop":1611.63,"duration":2.55},{"text":"I submit that it had been appealed with Burns, The result would’ve been the same as Burns.","start":1611.63,"stop":1618.018,"duration":6.39},{"text":"The continuation of the contract is a two-party affair.","start":1618.018,"stop":1622.976,"duration":4.96},{"text":"The contract does not run with the business, as Mr. Justice Marshall says.","start":1622.976,"stop":1629.083,"duration":6.11},{"text":"It is something which is a matter of consent, and both the company and the Union must consent for the contract to continue in effect, and this Court pointed out in Burns the policy considerations which require that.","start":1629.083,"stop":1647.561,"duration":18.48},{"text":"Court pointed out that there could be considerations on both sides of the bargain.","start":1647.561,"stop":1652.262,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Now, the duty -- the contractual, consensual duty to be bound by that contract and to arbitrate in accordance with the contract is inevitably intertwined with the status of successor.","start":1652.262,"stop":1673.1,"duration":20.84},{"text":"And the questions which the Court has put to Mr. Gold demonstrate the difference this case and Wiley, and indeed the difference between this case and the case like Lion Dry Goods.","start":1673.1,"stop":1685.584,"duration":12.48},{"text":"In Wiley, the plaintiffs who brought grievances had attained employment status with the employer, and thereafter, had grievances arise, differences with their employer.","start":1685.584,"stop":1701.084,"duration":15.5},{"text":"And this Court in Wiley held that those grievances which arose after the employment’s relationship existed rose subject arbitration under their contract of the prior employer.","start":1701.084,"stop":1714.086,"duration":13},{"text":"There is certainly a serious question whether even that can stand today in view of the Court’s unanimous ruling that the contract does not survive.","start":1714.086,"stop":1723.547,"duration":9.46},{"text":"The question becomes, what is parameters for the arbitrator?","start":1723.547,"stop":1729.206,"duration":5.66},{"text":"What is the basis in which he can make a decision?","start":1729.206,"stop":1732.737,"duration":3.53},{"text":"But, in any event the contract cannot be a vehicle with which the persons who claim grievances under this contract can attain employment status with the new employer.","start":1732.737,"stop":1754.093,"duration":21.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tracy, in most situations where someone buys a company, buys the assets and succeeds and continues to run the business.","start":1754.093,"stop":1765.482,"duration":11.39},{"text":"Surely, that purchaser must take account of other kinds of contracts, other kinds of obligations that the buyer has.","start":1765.482,"stop":1779.71,"duration":14.23},{"text":"In my state, if you bought a business, it didn’t take account of some of the debts that your seller owed and if he didn’t go through certain procedures and give them a chance to come in and make a claim, you’re going to be in trouble.","start":1779.71,"stop":1799.098,"duration":19.39}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that is true.","start":1799.098,"stop":1800.925,"duration":1.83},{"text":"That is a matter of statute.","start":1800.925,"stop":1802.969,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I agree with that.","start":1802.969,"stop":1803.965,"duration":1},{"text":"I agree with that.","start":1803.965,"stop":1806.729,"duration":2.76},{"text":"Bought Sales Acts and things like that.","start":1806.729,"stop":1810.252,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Now, I take it the Union, the employees are saying “We’re the only obligees of the seller that aren’t going to be taken care of” in some way.","start":1810.252,"stop":1825.9,"duration":15.65}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I agree.","start":1825.9,"stop":1828.144,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, your client bought the business.","start":1828.144,"stop":1830.966,"duration":2.82},{"text":"He knew he had a contract that says it bound the successor.","start":1830.966,"stop":1834.889,"duration":3.92},{"text":"And you wrote a letter and said remotely bound, but I will buy them ever the less.","start":1834.889,"stop":1839.957,"duration":5.07},{"text":"Now, the suggestion is, it’s a National Labor Law, says that you can’t avoid that successorship clause like that.","start":1839.957,"stop":1847.839,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, I submit that there certainly is a statutory requirement that we honor the contract, I understand when you asked that question yesterday and you didn’t get a very clear answer, but we know that successorship is not a statutory doctrine.","start":1847.839,"stop":1862.02,"duration":14.18},{"text":"It’s a Board and Court doctrine.","start":1862.02,"stop":1864.445,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I see.","start":1864.445,"stop":1865.014,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, there are some contracts which perhaps by Bought Sales Act or other statutory enactment, maybe become an obligation of a purchaser, but there are many others who do not.","start":1865.014,"stop":1876.667,"duration":11.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"You think Congress would enact legislation which would make this contract binding on successors such as your client?","start":1876.667,"stop":1885.545,"duration":8.88}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor, I believe that Congress could --","start":1885.545,"stop":1888.958,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s the approach in this new service contract.","start":1888.958,"stop":1891.404,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Exactly.","start":1891.404,"stop":1892.5,"duration":1.1},{"text":"Exactly, Your Honor, I believe that the fact that they enacted that kind indicates that if they had dared to go further and cover the kind of situation that is here today, they could well have done so by legislation.","start":1892.5,"stop":1903.4,"duration":10.9}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So far the most relevant provision is a provision that says that an employer isn’t bound to agree with the contract.","start":1903.4,"stop":1914.111,"duration":10.71},{"text":"That you can’t impose a provision of a contract on an Employer through the process of collective bargaining.","start":1914.111,"stop":1921.638,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that is Section 9 (d) of the Act.","start":1921.638,"stop":1924.8,"duration":3.16},{"text":"That’s the holding of this Court in H.K. Porter, and the argument that somehow in other -- it might be different that 9 (d) which is a statement in the National Labor Relations Act somehow doesn’t apply in an enforcement of contract situation just cannot stand.","start":1924.8,"stop":1945.06,"duration":20.26},{"text":"This Court has recognized there must be one body of law.","start":1945.06,"stop":1948.641,"duration":3.58},{"text":"I referred yesterday to the Lincoln Mills decision.","start":1948.641,"stop":1952.342,"duration":3.7},{"text":"Counsel this morning referred to the Lucas Flower decision of this Court.","start":1952.342,"stop":1956.352,"duration":4.01},{"text":"And in Lucas Flower, this Court said “The possibility that individual contract terms might have different meanings under State and Federal Law would inevitably exert a disruptive influence upon both the negotiation and administration of collective agreements.”","start":1956.352,"stop":1972.602,"duration":16.25},{"text":"If it can’t have different meanings, under State and Federal Law, cannot have different meanings in a Board case as compared with a Court case.","start":1972.602,"stop":1981.589,"duration":8.99},{"text":"We submit that clearly, it cannot, and returning Mr. Chief Justice to the question you raised yesterday relative to the short hiatus, is certainly that is an aspect to be considered in determining whether there is a continuity of the business, but there are many factors.","start":1981.589,"stop":2001.983,"duration":20.39},{"text":"Again, going to Mr. Justice White’s questions, there are many factors which determine the successorship status, and this Court has carefully considered them.","start":2001.983,"stop":2012.954,"duration":10.97},{"text":"Mr. Justice Rehnquist was concerned with them in the Burns case.","start":2012.954,"stop":2016.814,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Tracy, listen, why as he point out yesterday, the Court did not go on and discuss what the scope of the arbitration was?","start":2016.814,"stop":2024.738,"duration":7.92},{"text":"Now, I assume that you would concede that some successors might express they want to assume the contract.","start":2024.738,"stop":2032.041,"duration":7.3},{"text":"As your client -- as you know your client did.","start":2032.041,"stop":2035.659,"duration":3.62},{"text":"And that maybe, that nothing was said in the purchase of the sale about it.","start":2035.659,"stop":2040.916,"duration":5.26},{"text":"And there maybe an issue especially if the successor takes over a majority employees.","start":2040.916,"stop":2047.08,"duration":6.16},{"text":"There maybe an issue as to whether there was an assumption or not, or whether what the agreement was, and that kind of an issue submitted to an arbitrator, I would think would be wholly proper.","start":2047.08,"stop":2058.034,"duration":10.95}]},{"speakerName":"James D. Tracy","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree with you, Your Honor, and I believe that is the real meaning of the Wiley decision, and that’s the full meaning of the Wiley decision.","start":2058.034,"stop":2066.728,"duration":8.69},{"text":"You cannot boot scrap the successorship doctrine without retention of employees, or hiring of employees by the new employer into a requirement that he must take the employees, and therefore must recognize the Union, unless you are really going to say as Mr. Justice White said that you’re going to take a very large bite out of Burns.","start":2066.728,"stop":2093.205,"duration":26.48},{"text":"There is in Burns a decision which was unanimous as to the effect of the contract.","start":2093.205,"stop":2100.73,"duration":7.53},{"text":"And that decision is not consistent with the position of respondent in this case, or the position of the court below.","start":2100.73,"stop":2108.804,"duration":8.07},{"text":"It is consistent with the petitioner’s position.","start":2108.804,"stop":2112.567,"duration":3.76},{"text":"We request therefore, that the Court reverse the decision below.","start":2112.567,"stop":2117.43,"duration":4.86}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Tracy.","start":2117.43,"stop":2118.498,"duration":1.07},{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Gold.","start":2118.498,"stop":2119.406,"duration":0.91},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2119.406,"stop":2121.821,"duration":2.41}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Mar  19 - 20, 1974","petitioner":"Howard Johnson Company, Inc.","respondent":"Detroit Local Joint Executive Board, Hotel & Restaurant Employees & Bartenders International Union, AFL-CIO","docket":"73-631","citation":"417 US 249 (1974)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/417/249","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 3, 1974"}